2026-07-01 | Find the Safest Path in a Grid

	Question
Return the maximum possible safeness factor.
	Key Insight
The problem has two phases.
Phase 1:
Compute, for every cell, its minimum Manhattan distance from any thief.
This can be done using Multi-Source BFS by starting BFS simultaneously from every thief.
Let:
		dist[i][j]
	be the distance of cell (i,j) from its nearest thief.
Phase 2:
Suppose we want to know whether a path exists whose every cell has:
		dist ≥ X
This is easy to check using a normal BFS.
If such a path exists for X, then it also exists for every value smaller than X.
So the answer is monotonic, allowing Binary Search.
	Approach
1.	Run Multi-Source BFS from all thief cells to compute the nearest thief distance for every cell.
2.	Binary search the safeness factor.
3.	For each candidate value:
		- Start BFS from (0,0).
		- Move only to cells having distance ≥ candidate.
		- If (n−1,n−1) is reachable, the candidate is valid.
4.	Return the largest valid value.
	Time Complexity
	O(n² log n)
	- Multi-source BFS: O(n²)
	- Binary Search: O(log n)
	- BFS for each check: O(n²)
	Space Complexity
	O(n²)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    vector<pair<int,int>> dir = {{1,0},{-1,0},{0,1},{0,-1}};
    bool canReach(vector<vector<int>>& dist, int safe) {
        int n = dist.size();
        if(dist[0][0] < safe)
            return false;
        queue<pair<int,int>> q;
        vector<vector<int>> vis(n, vector<int>(n,0));
        q.push({0,0});
        vis[0][0] = 1;
        while(!q.empty()) {
            auto [x,y] = q.front();
            q.pop();
            if(x == n-1 && y == n-1)
                return true;
            for(auto &[dx,dy] : dir) {
                int nx = x + dx;
                int ny = y + dy;
                if(nx>=0 && ny>=0 && nx<n && ny<n &&
                   !vis[nx][ny] &&
                   dist[nx][ny] >= safe) {
                    vis[nx][ny] = 1;
                    q.push({nx,ny});
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
    int maximumSafenessFactor(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int n = grid.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dist(n, vector<int>(n,-1));
        queue<pair<int,int>> q;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++) {
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++) {
                if(grid[i][j]==1) {
                    dist[i][j]=0;
                    q.push({i,j});
                }
            }
        }
        while(!q.empty()) {
            auto [x,y]=q.front();
            q.pop();
            for(auto &[dx,dy]:dir) {
                int nx=x+dx;
                int ny=y+dy;
                if(nx>=0 && ny>=0 && nx<n && ny<n &&
                   dist[nx][ny]==-1) {
                    dist[nx][ny]=dist[x][y]+1;
                    q.push({nx,ny});
                }
            }
        }
        int low=0, high=2*n, ans=0;
        while(low<=high){
            int mid=(low+high)/2;
            if(canReach(dist,mid)){
                ans=mid;
                low=mid+1;
            }
            else{
                high=mid-1;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Example
	Input
		grid =
		[
		  [1,0,0],
		  [0,0,0],
		  [0,0,1]
		]
	Distance from nearest thief
		[
		  [0,1,2],
		  [1,2,1],
		  [2,1,0]
		]
	The best path keeps the minimum distance as large as possible.
	Output
		1
	Key Insight
	The problem is a classic **maximize the minimum** problem. First, compute each cell's distance from the nearest thief using **Multi-Source BFS**. Then, use **Binary Search** on the answer and verify each candidate with a simple **BFS**, giving an overall complexity of **O(n² log n)**.
